controversial questions of religion, race, identity, and intermarriage.Richard Alba and Nancy Foner shed new light on questions at the heart of concerns about immigration. They analyze why immigrant religion is a more significant divide in Western Europe than in the United States, where race is a more severe obstacle. They look at why, despite fears in Europe about the rise of immigrant ghettoes, residential segregation is much less of a problem for immigrant minorities there than in the United States. They explore why everywhere, growing economic inequality and the proliferation of precarious, low-wage jobs pose dilemmas for the second generation. They also evaluate perspectives often proposed to explain the success of immigrant integration in certain countries, including nationally specific models, the political economy, and the histories of Canada and the United States as settler societies.Strangers No More delves into issues of pivotal importance for the present and future of Western societies, where immigrants and their children form ever-larger shares of the population.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aChildren of immigrantsxCultural assimilation. 0aEmigration and immigrationxReligious aspects. 0aSocial integrationzEurope, Western. 0aSocial integrationzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh  aAfrican immigrants.  aChristians.  aMuslims.  aNorth America.  aU.S. civil rights movement.  aWestern Europe.  abelonging.  ablack ghettoes.  acolor-coded race.  ademographic transition.  adiverse neighborhoods.  aeconomic incorporation.  aeconomic inequality.  aeconomic migration.  aeconomic situations.  aeconomic structures.  aeducation.  aelectoral representation.  aghettoization.  agovernment policies.  ahuman-capital immigrants.  aidenti